=====Behind the scenes=====
Director Herbert Wise felt that ''Julius Caesar'' should be set in the [[Elizabethan era]], but as per the emphasis on realism, he instead set it in a [[Roman Empire|Roman ''milieu'']].<ref>Willis, p. 93.</ref> Wise argued that the play "is not really a Roman play. It's an Elizabethan play and it's a view of Rome from an Elizabethan standpoint." Regarding setting the play in Shakespeare's day, Wise stated that, "I don't think that's right for the audience we will be getting. It's not a jaded theatre audience seeing the play for the umpteenth time: for them that would be an interesting approach and might throw new light on the play. But for an audience many of whom won't have seen the play before, I believe it would only be confusing."<ref>{{cite book | editor-last=Wilders | editor-first=John | title=Julius Caesar | series=The BBC TV Shakespeare | location=London | publisher=BBC Books | year=1979 | page=[https://archive.org/details/juliuscaesar0000shak/page/20 20] | isbn=9780831752767 | url=https://archive.org/details/juliuscaesar0000shak/page/20 }}</ref>

The ''Prefaces to Shakespeare'' episode for ''Julius Caesar'' was presented by [[Ronald Pickup]], who had played Octavius Caesar in a 1964 [[Royal Court Theatre]] production directed by [[Lindsay Anderson]], and Cassius in a 1977 [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] production directed by [[John Schlesinger]]. The ''Shakespeare in Perspective'' episode was presented by political commentator [[Jonathan Dimbleby]].

