=====Behind the scenes=====
Director John Gorrie interpreted ''Twelfth Night'' as an [[English country house]] comedy, and incorporated influences ranging from [[Luigi Pirandello]]'s play ''[[The Rules of the Game (play)|Il Gioco delle Parti]]'' to [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s ''[[Upstairs, Downstairs (1971 TV series)|Upstairs, Downstairs]]''.<ref name="Wiggins 4">Wiggins, p. 4.</ref> Gorrie also set the play during the [[English Civil War]] in the hopes the use of [[cavalier]]s and [[roundhead]]s would help focus the dramatisation of the conflict between [[festival|festivity]] and [[Puritan]]ism.<ref name="Wiggins 6"/> Gorrie wanted the episode to be as realistic as possible, and in designing Olivia's house, made sure that the geography of the building was practical. He then shot the episode in such a way that the audience becomes aware of the logical geography, often shooting characters entering and existing doorways into rooms and corridors.<ref>Willis, p. 191.</ref>

The ''Prefaces to Shakespeare'' episode for ''Twelfth Night'' was presented by [[Dorothy Tutin]] who had played Viola in a 1958 RSC production directed by Peter Hall. The ''Shakespeare in Perspective'' episode was presented by painter and poet [[David Jones (artist-poet)|David Jones]].

