=====Behind the scenes=====
[[File:BBC Richard III.jpg|thumb|The controversial final image of the episode â€“ the "reverse pietÃ " â€“ which divided critics, but which for director Jane Howell was a vital aspect of the thematic design of the production]]
This episode was filmed on the same set as the three ''Henry VI'' plays. However, designer Oliver Bayldon altered the set so it would appear to be a ruin, as England reached its lowest point of chaos.<ref name="Warren"/> In the same vein, the costumes became more and more monotone as the four plays went on; ''The First Part of Henry the Sixt'' features brightly coloured costumes which clearly distinguish the various combatants from one another, but by ''The Tragedy of Richard III'', everyone fights in similarly coloured dark costumes, with little to differentiate one army from another.<ref name="Willems"/>

As this version of ''Richard III'' functioned as the fourth part of a series, it meant that much of the text usually cut in standalone productions could remain. The most obvious beneficiary of this was the character of Margaret, whose role, if not removed completely, is usually truncated. Textual editor David Snodin was especially pleased that a filmed version of ''Richard III'' was finally presenting Margaret's full role.<ref>See {{cite book | last=Taylor | first=Neil  | title=Two Types of Television Shakespeare | journal=Shakespeare Survey | volume=39 | year=1986 | page=105 | url=http://universitypublishingonline.org/cambridge/shakespeare/chapter.jsf?bid=CBO9781139053167&cid=CBO9781139053167A011 | accessdate=13 September 2014 | doi=10.1017/CCOL0521327571.008| isbn=9781139053167  }}</ref> Director Jane Howell also saw the unedited nature of the tetralogy as important for Richard himself, arguing that without the three ''Henry VI'' plays "it is impossible to appreciate Richard except as some sort of diabolical [[megalomania]]c," whereas in the full context of the tetralogy "you've seen why he is created, you know how such a man can be created: he was brought up in war, he saw and knew nothing else from his father but the struggle for the crown, and if you've been brought up to fight, if you've got a great deal of energy, and physical handicaps, what do you do? You take to intrigue and plotting."<ref>Quoted in {{cite book | last=Richmond | first=Hugh M. | title=Shakespeare in Performance: Richard III | location=Manchester | publisher=Manchester University Press | year=1989 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/kingrichardiii0000rich/page/90 90â€“91] | isbn=9780719027246 | url=https://archive.org/details/kingrichardiii0000rich/page/90 }}</ref>

The production is unusual amongst filmed ''Richard''s insofar as no one is killed on camera, other than Richard himself. This was a conscious choice on the part of Howell; "you see nobody killed; just people going away, being taken away â€“ so much like today; they're just removed. There's a knock on the door and people are almost willing to go. There's no way out of it."<ref>Quoted in {{cite book | editor-last=Eccles | editor-first=Mark | title=The Tragedy of Richard III | location=New York | publisher=Signet | series=Signet Classic Shakespeare | year=1998 | origyear=1964 | edition=Second Revised | page=[https://archive.org/details/tragedyofrichard02shak/page/244 244] | isbn=9780451526953 | url=https://archive.org/details/tragedyofrichard02shak/page/244 }}</ref>

Controversially, the episode ended with Margaret sitting atop a pyramid of corpses (played by all of the major actors who had appeared throughout the tetralogy) cradling Richard's dead body and laughing manically, an image Edward Burns refers to as "a blasphemous ''[[pietÃ ]]''."<ref>{{cite book | editor-last=Burns | editor-first=Edward | title=King Henry VI Part 1 | location=London | publisher=Thompson Learning | series=The Arden Shakespeare, Third Series | year=2000 | page=306 | isbn=9781903436431}}</ref> Howell herself referred to it as a "reverse pietÃ ," and defended it by arguing that the tetralogy is bigger than ''Richard III'', so to end by simply showing Richard's death and Richmond's coronation is to diminish the roles that have gone before; the vast amount of death that has preceded the end of ''Richard III'' cannot be ignored.<ref>Willis, p. 179.</ref> R. Chris Hassel Jr. remarks of this scene that "our last taste is not the restoration of order and good governance, but of chaos and arbitrary violence."<ref>{{cite book | last=Hassel Jr. | first=R. Chris | title=Songs of Death: Performance, Interpretation and the Text of Richard III | location=Lincoln, NE | publisher=University of Nebraska Press | year=1987 | page=28 | isbn=9780803223417}}</ref> Hugh M. Richmond says the scene gives the production a "cynical conclusion," as "it leaves our impressions of the new King Henry VII's reign strongly coloured by Margaret's malevolent glee at the destruction of her enemies that Henry has accomplished for her."<ref>{{cite book | last=Richmond | first=Hugh M. | title=Shakespeare in Performance: Richard III | location=Manchester | publisher=Manchester University Press | year=1989 | page=[https://archive.org/details/kingrichardiii0000rich/page/12 12] | isbn=9780719027246 | url=https://archive.org/details/kingrichardiii0000rich/page/12 }}</ref>

Howell's presentation of the complete first historical tetralogy was one of the most lauded achievements of the entire BBC series, and prompted Stanley Wells to argue that the productions were "probably purer than any version given in the theatre since Shakespeare's time."<ref name="Stanley"/> Michael Mannheim was similarly impressed, calling the tetralogy "a fascinating, fast paced and surprisingly tight-knit study in political and national deterioration."<ref name="Mannheim"/>

At 239 minutes, this production was the longest episode in the entire series, and when the series was released on DVD in 2005, it was the only adaptation split over two disks. Of the 3,887 lines comprising the ''First Folio'' text of the play, Howell cut only 72; roughly 1.8% of the total.<ref name="Kossak">{{cite book | last=Kossak | first=Saskia | title="Frame My Face to All Occasions": Shakespeare's Richard III on Screen | location=Berlin | publisher=BraumÃ¼ller | year=2005 | page=188 | isbn=9783700314929}}</ref>

The ''Prefaces to Shakespeare'' episode for ''The Tragedy of Richard III'' was presented by [[Edward Woodward]] who had played Richard in a 1982 [[Ludlow#Festivals and fayres|Ludlow Festival]] production directed by [[David William]]. The ''Shakespeare in Perspective'' episode was presented by novelist [[Rosemary Anne Sisson]].<ref>An analysis of this production can be found in {{cite book | last=Richmond | first=Hugh M. | title=Shakespeare in Performance: Richard III | location=Manchester | publisher=Manchester University Press | year=1989 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/kingrichardiii0000rich/page/89 89â€“110] | isbn=9780719027246 | url=https://archive.org/details/kingrichardiii0000rich/page/89 }} An analysis of the entire tetralogy can be found in Willis, pp. 175â€“185.</ref>

